  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, an H-1B visa can be extended beyond the standard six-year limit if the visa holder has an approved I-140 petition for an employment-based green card. This is possible even if the I-140 was filed by a previous employer. According to the American Competitiveness in the Twenty-First Century Act (AC21), as long as the I-140 is approved and certain conditions are met, the H-1B holder can request extensions in one-year or three-year increments beyond the six-year limit. \n\nIt is important to ensure that the I-140 has not been revoked for fraud or misrepresentation by the previous employer and that the priority date has not been reached for green card processing in order to qualify for these extensions. The new employer can file an H-1B extension petition, referencing the approved I-140, to continue the foreign employee's H-1B status beyond the six-year period. Always consider consulting an immigration attorney for advice specific to individual situations.",
